 economic reality from several different perspectives. An ambitious introductory essay by Richard Swedberg uses many new sources to enhance our understanding of Schumpeter's life and work and to help analyze his fascinating character. This essay stresses Schumpeter's ability to draw on several social sciences in his study of capitalism. Some of the articles in the anthology are published for the first time. The most important of these are Schumpeter's Lowell Lectures from 1941, "An Economic Interpretation of Our Time." Also included is the transcript of his lecture "Can Capitalism Survive?" (1936) and the high-spirited debate that followed. The anthology contains many of Schumpeter's classical sociological articles, such as his essays on the tax state, imperialism, and social classes. And, finally, there are lesser known articles on the future of private enterprise, on the concept of rationality in the social sciences, and on the work of Max Weber, with whom Schumpeter collaborated on several occasions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalism. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aBeccaria.  aBiedermann Bank.  aCantillon.  aCorn Laws.  aGerman Socialization Commission.  aGoddard.  aGraz University of Technology.  aGuizot.  aHarvard University.  aHegelianism.  aHitlerism.  aHuskisson.  aImperial Federation.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aJapan.  aKondratieff waves.  aLamprecht.  aLondon School of Economics.  aMarxism.  aNational Socialists.  aOmayyads.  aabsolutism.  aagriculture.  aaristocracy.  abanking.  abirth rate.  acapitalism.  acartels and trusts.  aclass struggle.  aconsumers.  acurrency stabilization.  ademocracy.  aeconomic frontier.  aefficiency.  aempirical verification.  aestate tax system.  aethnology.  aexport mon